-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Installation instructions
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

There are three steps to get the BrewControl server up and running:
1. Prepare hardware
2. Compile or download the server
3. Launch the server

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Prepare hardware
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Before you can start using this software, you need to set up the hardware. You 
need
- a Raspberry Pi,
- a DS18B20 1-wire Temperature Sensor and a 4.7 kOhm resistor
- some sort of a relay (preferably a Solid State Relay)
- some button

Connect the button to GPIO1 and Ground.
Connect the Relay to GPIO4 and Ground.
Connect the DS18B10 to the Raspberry Pi:
- Pin1 GROUND to 0V/Ground
- Pin2 DATA  to GPIO7
- Pin3 POWER to 3V3

See http://pi4j.com/pins/model-b-rev2.html for a pin layout.

Install the current Raspbian operating system to an SD card and boot the 
RaspberryPi. Make sure the kernel modules "w1-gpio" and "w1-therm" are loaded 
when the system boot up by listing them in the /etc/modules, each in a new 
line. Add the line "dtoverlay=w1-gpio" to /boot/config.txt. Shutdown or reboot
the Raspberry Pi.
 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Compile or download the server
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Run 
mvn package
on the source and copy the jar file to the Raspberry Pi.
You may also download the jar file from the BrewControl github website.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Launch the server
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Install java on the Raspberry Pi: 
sudo apt-get install oracle-java8-jdk

Execute the jar file by running 
sudo java -jar brewcontrol-0.1.0.jar [command]
on the Raspberry Pi. This launches the standalone brewcontrol server.

Choose your command:
gpio: This really is what you want. (GPIO-Pins are used.)
piface: This uses the Piface extension board Relay1 and Button1.
simulate:  Simulate doesn't use any physical buttons, sensors or relays, it
just simulates these devices.

Please note that brewcontrol requires sudo permission as it uses pi4j which
uses wiringpi, which requires superuser rights.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Support, bugs, reature requests
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Please see the BrewControl github website for ways to get in touch with the 
developer.